 *
 * Tier A · Foundations.
 *
 * Definitional content drawn from primary sources:
 *   - Kumar 2025 IJNDC §2.1 — entanglement, Bell states, Bell pair
 *     as the network-resource primitive.
 *   - Kozlowski et al. RFC 9340 §3 — Bell pair as the link-layer
 *     service of a quantum network.
 *   - Bell 1964 — original theorem, no local hidden variables.
 *   - Bennett et al. PRL 70 1895 (1993) — quantum teleportation.
 *   - Wootters & Zurek Nature 299 802 (1982) — no-cloning theorem.
 *   - Bennett et al. PRA 54 3824 (1996) — BBPSSW distillation.
 *   - Żukowski et al. PRL 71 4287 (1993) — entanglement swapping.
 *   - Wehner Science 362 eaam9288 (2018) — vision for the road ahead.
 */
import Infographic from "../layouts/Infographic.astro";
import Center from "../components/Center.astro";
import Stack from "../components/Stack.astro";
import Grid from "../components/Grid.astro";
import SiteNav from "../components/SiteNav.astro";
import SourceNote from "../components/SourceNote.astro";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";
import Math from "../components/Math.astro";
import { url } from "../lib/url";

const sections = [
  { id: "overview",     label: "Overview" },
  { id: "definition",   label: "What entanglement is" },
  { id: "bell-pairs",   label: "The four Bell pairs" },
  { id: "why-deliver",  label: "Why deliver Bell pairs" },
  { id: "uses",         label: "What a Bell pair lets you do" },
  { id: "generation",   label: "How Bell pairs are made" },
  { id: "requirements", label: "What it takes to deliver" },
];
---

<Infographic
  title="Entanglement and Bell pairs"
  description="Entanglement is the multi-qubit phenomenon that makes quantum networking a separate discipline. Bell pairs are the unit of currency in every quantum-network protocol. This page covers the definition of entanglement, the four Bell pairs, what a delivered Bell pair lets you do (teleportation, swapping, distillation), how Bell pairs are generated, and what a Bell-pair delivery network needs to operate."
  references={[
    "bell-1964",
    "bennett-pra-1996",
    "bennett-prl-1993",
    "duan-nature-414",
    "forbes-rpp-2025",
    "knaut-nature-2024",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "kwiat-prl-1995",
    "muralidharan-scirep-2016",
    "sangouard-rmp-83",
    "wootters-nature-1982",
    "yin-science-2017",
    "zukowski-prl-1993",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="entanglement" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Entanglement and Bell pairs</h1>
        <p>
          A qubit by itself is a richer object than a classical bit, but it is still a
          local thing. <strong>Entanglement</strong> is the multi-qubit phenomenon that makes
          quantum networking a separate discipline — not "wider-bandwidth classical
          networking" but a different category of service.
        </p>
        <p>
          The unit of currency is the <strong>Bell pair</strong>: a single pair of qubits in
          a specific maximally entangled state, with one qubit at each of two endpoints.
          Once a Bell pair is delivered between two distant nodes, users can teleport
          arbitrary qubits through it, extract a cryptographic key, or run a distributed
          protocol. The whole of quantum networking reduces to one goal: deliver Bell pairs
          at adequate rate, fidelity, and reach <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="definition" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What entanglement is</h2>
        <p>
          A single qubit's state is <Math tex="\\alpha|0\\rangle + \\beta|1\\rangle" /> with
          <Math tex="|\\alpha|^2 + |\\beta|^2 = 1" />, and measurement in the computational
          basis collapses it to <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> or <Math tex="|1\\rangle" /> with
          probabilities <Math tex="|\\alpha|^2" /> and <Math tex="|\\beta|^2" />. Entanglement
          is what happens when two of these are composed into a single joint state
          <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          For two qubits <Math tex="A" /> and <Math tex="B" />, the joint state lives in a
          four-dimensional space with basis vectors <Math tex="|00\\rangle" />,
          <Math tex="|01\\rangle" />, <Math tex="|10\\rangle" />, <Math tex="|11\\rangle" />.
          The notation is just a stacked pair: <Math tex="|00\\rangle" /> means
          <em>qubit A is in <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> and qubit B is in <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /></em>;
          <Math tex="|01\\rangle" /> means <em>A in <Math tex="|0\\rangle" />, B in <Math tex="|1\\rangle" /></em>;
          and so on. A general two-qubit state is a complex superposition over all four of
          these joint outcomes, with amplitudes whose squared magnitudes sum to 1.
        </p>
        <p>
          A <strong>separable</strong> state is one that can be written as a tensor product
          of two independent single-qubit states,
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle_{AB} = |\\psi\\rangle_A \\otimes |\\phi\\rangle_B" /> —
          each qubit has its own state, and the joint state is just <q>A's state and B's
          state side by side</q>. An <strong>entangled</strong> state is one that
          <em>cannot</em> be written that way: the two qubits do not have individual states
          of their own, only a single shared state. The canonical example is the Bell state
        </p>

        <Math display tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle = \\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\bigl(|00\\rangle + |11\\rangle\\bigr)" />

        <p>
          The pair is in an equal superposition of <q>both qubits are 0</q> and <q>both
          qubits are 1</q>. The <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}" /> in front is the
          normalising amplitude — Born's rule turns each amplitude into a probability by
          squaring its magnitude, so each outcome has probability
          <Math tex="(1/\\sqrt{2})^2 = \\tfrac{1}{2}" />. When Alice and Bob measure their
          qubits in the computational basis (the standard <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> /
          <Math tex="|1\\rangle" /> basis — H or V for photon polarisation), two things
          happen at once:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Each individual outcome is random.</strong> Alice sees 0 half the time
            and 1 half the time; same for Bob. Looked at on its own, either side is a fair
            coin.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The outcomes always agree.</strong> The joint result is either 00 or 11,
            each with probability ½. The cross-terms 01 and 10 have amplitude zero — they
            never happen. Alice and Bob's coins are perfectly correlated, even though
            either coin in isolation looks random.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Each qubit is locally indeterminate, yet the pair is deterministically correlated.
          The state has no factorisation into A and B parts, and the correlation persists
          regardless of how far apart the two qubits are. Bell's theorem proved that this
          correlation cannot be reproduced by any local classical pre-arrangement: no shared
          random seed agreed on in advance recovers the same statistics across all
          measurement bases <SourceNote id="bell-1964" />.
        </p>

        <figure class="epr">
          <svg viewBox="0 -10 600 250" role="img"
               aria-label="Entangled-photon source emitting a Bell pair to Alice and Bob, with correlated measurement outcomes"
               data-eps>
            {/* Polarisation encoding: a horizontal bar (—) is a
                photon in |0⟩ (H-polarised); a vertical bar (|) is
                |1⟩ (V-polarised). The same shape runs through the
                detector indicators and the photon glyphs during
                flight. No colour is used to encode the basis. */}

            {/* Fuzzy "probability cloud" drawn around each in-flight
                photon: opaque core, soft halo fading to transparent.
                Signifies that the photon is in a superposition until
                measurement; the bar inside shows the polarisation axis
                the measurement could project onto. */}
            <defs>
              <radialGradient id="eps-photon-cloud">
                <stop offset="0%"  stop-color="var(--color-accent)" stop-opacity="1"/>
                <stop offset="35%" stop-color="var(--color-accent)" stop-opacity="0.92"/>
                <stop offset="70%" stop-color="var(--color-accent)" stop-opacity="0.45"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--color-accent)" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
            </defs>

            {/* Bell state label. The two-digit tspans (00 / 11) carry
                the data-eps-ket marker and are highlighted on
                measurement; the backing rects are positioned at run
                time from each tspan's bounding box, then shown to
                give a white-on-black inversion of just the digits. */}
            <rect data-eps-ket-bg="00" fill="var(--color-text)" opacity="0" rx="2"/>
            <rect data-eps-ket-bg="11" fill="var(--color-text)" opacity="0" rx="2"/>
            <text x="300" y="10" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-state">
              |Φ⁺⟩ = ( |<tspan data-eps-ket="00">00</tspan>⟩ + |<tspan data-eps-ket="11">11</tspan>⟩ ) / √2
            </text>

            {/* Static dashed flight paths from the EPS to each
                station's PBS. */}
            <line x1="278" y1="80" x2="80" y2="80"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="5,4" opacity="0.65"/>
            <line x1="322" y1="80" x2="520" y2="80"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="5,4" opacity="0.65"/>

            {/* Entangled-photon source — QuISP EPPS network icon
                (sfc-aqua/quisp, Van Meter et al.). The icon is the
                shared visual vocabulary for quantum-network
                topologies across the workspace. Rendered white-on-
                black for higher contrast against the page surface:
                a filled dark backdrop sits behind the icon, and the
                icon's black strokes are inverted to white. */}
            <circle cx="300" cy="80" r="24" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <image href={url("/icons/quisp/EPPS.svg")} x="276" y="56" width="48" height="48" style="filter: invert(1);"/>
            <text x="300" y="128" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-caption">entangled-photon source</text>

            {/* Alice apparatus. A polarising beam splitter (PBS, the
                small square with a diagonal interface) splits the
                incoming beam into two output beams — one goes
                up-and-outward to D₀ (the H detector, outcome 0), the
                other goes down-and-outward to D₁ (V, outcome 1). The
                photon traverses the chosen output beam at the moment
                of measurement, so the eye sees which way it went.
                Border thickens briefly when a detector fires. */}
            <text x="50" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-label">Alice</text>
            <g data-eps-det="A0">
              <rect x="20" y="36" width="24" height="18" rx="3"
                    fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line data-eps-result="A0" x1="26" y1="45" x2="38" y2="45"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.18"/>
            </g>
            <text x="12" y="48" text-anchor="end" class="epr-out" dominant-baseline="middle">0</text>
            <line x1="62" y1="72" x2="44" y2="54"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,3" opacity="0.6"/>
            <g data-eps-pbs>
              <rect x="62" y="72" width="16" height="16"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line x1="62" y1="72" x2="78" y2="88"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            </g>
            <line x1="62" y1="88" x2="44" y2="106"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,3" opacity="0.6"/>
            <g data-eps-det="A1">
              <rect x="20" y="106" width="24" height="18" rx="3"
                    fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line data-eps-result="A1" x1="32" y1="109" x2="32" y2="121"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.18"/>
            </g>
            <text x="12" y="116" text-anchor="end" class="epr-out" dominant-baseline="middle">1</text>

            {/* Bob apparatus (mirror image of Alice). */}
            <text x="550" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-label">Bob</text>
            <g data-eps-det="B0">
              <rect x="556" y="36" width="24" height="18" rx="3"
                    fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line data-eps-result="B0" x1="562" y1="45" x2="574" y2="45"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.18"/>
            </g>
            <text x="588" y="48" text-anchor="start" class="epr-out" dominant-baseline="middle">0</text>
            <line x1="538" y1="72" x2="556" y2="54"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,3" opacity="0.6"/>
            <g data-eps-pbs>
              <rect x="522" y="72" width="16" height="16"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line x1="522" y1="72" x2="538" y2="88"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            </g>
            <line x1="538" y1="88" x2="556" y2="106"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3,3" opacity="0.6"/>
            <g data-eps-det="B1">
              <rect x="556" y="106" width="24" height="18" rx="3"
                    fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <line data-eps-result="B1" x1="568" y1="109" x2="568" y2="121"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.18"/>
            </g>
            <text x="588" y="116" text-anchor="start" class="epr-out" dominant-baseline="middle">1</text>

            {/* Animated photon glyphs. Each photon has two leg phases:
                an inward leg from the EPS to the PBS (drawn as a fuzzy
                cloud — no polarisation axis yet) and an outward leg
                from the PBS to whichever detector it ends up at
                (drawn as a sharp H or V bar, depending on outcome).
                The transition happens instantaneously at the PBS. */}
            <g data-eps-photon="L" transform="translate(278 80)" opacity="0">
              <circle data-eps-cloud r="11" fill="url(#eps-photon-cloud)"/>
              <line data-eps-bar x1="-8" y1="0" x2="8" y2="0"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0"/>
            </g>
            <g data-eps-photon="R" transform="translate(322 80)" opacity="0">
              <circle data-eps-cloud r="11" fill="url(#eps-photon-cloud)"/>
              <line data-eps-bar x1="-8" y1="0" x2="8" y2="0"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0"/>
            </g>

            {/* Per-side measurement history. Both sides accumulate
                the same string of outcomes (since the pair is
                correlated); the reader can read across to confirm
                the strings match and watch them grow without an
                obvious 0,1,0,1 pattern. */}
            <text x="70" y="160" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-history-label">history</text>
            <rect data-eps-history-bg="A" fill="var(--color-text)" opacity="0" rx="2"/>
            <text data-eps-history="A" x="70" y="180" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-history">—</text>

            <text x="530" y="160" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-history-label">history</text>
            <rect data-eps-history-bg="B" fill="var(--color-text)" opacity="0" rx="2"/>
            <text data-eps-history="B" x="530" y="180" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-history">—</text>

            {/* Correlation annotation */}
            <text x="300" y="220" text-anchor="middle" class="epr-caption">
              outcomes always match: 00 or 11, each with probability ½ — never 01 or 10
            </text>
          </svg>
          <figcaption>
            <ul class="epr-caption-list">
              <li>
                <strong>Source.</strong> The entangled-photon source (EPS) at the centre
                emits two photons in the joint state <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle" />,
                sending one to Alice and one to Bob. Most commonly a non-linear crystal
                pumped by a laser, in which one pump photon spontaneously down-converts
                into a pair of lower-energy photons correlated by the conservation laws
                of the conversion process.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Polarisation is one encoding among many.</strong> A photon can
                carry a qubit in polarisation, time-bin, phase, frequency-bin, or
                dual-rail form — the qubits subject covers the menu. The entanglement
                physics is the same in any encoding; polarisation is the most familiar
                and the easiest to picture.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Apparatus.</strong> Each station is a polarising beam splitter
                (PBS, the square with a diagonal interface) followed by two single-photon
                detectors. The outer-up detector D₀ clicks on the H component, the
                outer-down D₁ on V — so a single measurement always yields one click,
                and the slot that lit up identifies the outcome.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Both stations measure in the same basis.</strong> The PBSes here
                are both oriented H/V. The
                <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle" /> correlation holds only when Alice and
                Bob's measurement axes match — both could have chosen diagonal or any
                other axis and still seen perfect agreement, but a mismatch makes the
                outcomes follow Malus's law,
                <Math tex="P(\\text{agree}) = \\cos^2(\\theta_A - \\theta_B)" />, instead
                of locking step. The choice of basis matters; the choice of <em>which</em>
                basis (so long as both pick the same one) doesn't.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Inward leg, then split.</strong> On the inward leg each photon
                is a fuzzy cloud with no axis — the polarisation is undefined, in the
                superposition <Math tex="|00\\rangle + |11\\rangle" />. When the photon
                reaches the PBS it continues onto one of the two output beams as a
                sharp H or V bar, and the eye sees which way it went.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Time of measurement does not matter.</strong> Each cycle
                randomly picks which side measures first; you'll see one detector's
                border pulse, then the other's. The second outcome always matches the
                first — the running history under each detector is identical, and the
                running string is genuinely random (no <q>0,1,0,1</q> pattern; each
                cycle is an independent fair coin).
              </li>
            </ul>
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <script type="module" is:inline>
          // Entangled-photon-source animation. Each side's apparatus
          // is a polarising beam splitter (PBS) plus two single-photon
          // detectors: the upper detector clicks on H (outcome 0), the
          // lower clicks on V (outcome 1). Each cycle is staged as:
          //
          //   1. Both photons leave the EPS as fuzzy clouds — no
          //      polarisation axis, the joint state is |00⟩+|11⟩.
          //   2. The clouds arrive at each side's PBS and pause as
          //      clouds for a moment (still in superposition).
          //   3. One side measures first (chosen randomly per cycle).
          //      Its cloud disappears and one of its two detectors
          //      lights up — border flashes thicker, the H or V slot
          //      indicator inside brightens, and the outcome is
          //      appended to that side's running history. The other
          //      photon is still a cloud at its PBS, waiting.
          //   4. ~450 ms later the other detector measures — same
          //      outcome, same reveal, same history append.
          //
          // Outcomes are independent uniform 50/50 per cycle (no
          // fixed pattern). prefers-reduced-motion → static frame.
          const eps = document.querySelector("[data-eps]");
          if (eps) {
            const photonL = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-photon="L"]');
            const photonR = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-photon="R"]');
            const lCloud = photonL.querySelector('[data-eps-cloud]');
            const rCloud = photonR.querySelector('[data-eps-cloud]');
            const lBar = photonL.querySelector('[data-eps-bar]');
            const rBar = photonR.querySelector('[data-eps-bar]');
            const a0 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-result="A0"]');
            const a1 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-result="A1"]');
            const b0 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-result="B0"]');
            const b1 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-result="B1"]');
            // Detector groups (rect + slot indicator). The rect inside
            // each group is what we thicken on pulse.
            const detRect = {
              A0: eps.querySelector('[data-eps-det="A0"] rect'),
              A1: eps.querySelector('[data-eps-det="A1"] rect'),
              B0: eps.querySelector('[data-eps-det="B0"] rect'),
              B1: eps.querySelector('[data-eps-det="B1"] rect'),
            };
            const aHist = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-history="A"]');
            const bHist = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-history="B"]');
            const aHistBg = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-history-bg="A"]');
            const bHistBg = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-history-bg="B"]');
            const k00 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-ket="00"]');
            const k11 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-ket="11"]');
            const bg00 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-ket-bg="00"]');
            const bg11 = eps.querySelector('[data-eps-ket-bg="11"]');

            // Size each highlight rect to fit its digit tspan, with a
            // tiny pad so the inverted text doesn't kiss the edges.
            // Deferred to the next frame so the SVG text has been
            // laid out and getBBox returns real values.
            function positionKetHighlight(rect, tspan) {
              const bb = tspan.getBBox();
              rect.setAttribute("x", bb.x - 2);
              rect.setAttribute("y", bb.y - 1);
              rect.setAttribute("width", bb.width + 4);
              rect.setAttribute("height", bb.height + 2);
            }
            requestAnimationFrame(() => {
              positionKetHighlight(bg00, k00);
              positionKetHighlight(bg11, k11);
            });

            const SRC_L = 278, SRC_R = 322;
            const PBS_L = 70,  PBS_R = 530;
            const FLIGHT_Y = 80;
            // Detector centres — where the outward leg of each
            // photon ends up. Outcome 0 (H) goes up-and-outward;
            // outcome 1 (V) goes down-and-outward.
            const DET_POS = {
              A0: { x: 32,  y: 45  },
              A1: { x: 32,  y: 115 },
              B0: { x: 568, y: 45  },
              B1: { x: 568, y: 115 },
            };
            const HISTORY_LIMIT = 10;

            // Running history of detected outcomes, identical on both
            // sides because the pair is correlated. The last digit on
            // each side is rendered inside a tspan so we can toggle a
            // "fresh" class — bold + accent at the moment of
            // measurement; the previous digit reverts to normal weight
            // at the next measurement (no fade, classes flip when the
            // per-side text is rebuilt).
            const history = [];
            const SVG_NS = "http://www.w3.org/2000/svg";

            function renderHistorySide(target, fresh) {
              const bg = target === aHist ? aHistBg : bHistBg;
              while (target.firstChild) target.removeChild(target.firstChild);
              if (history.length === 0) {
                target.textContent = "—";
                bg.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
                return;
              }
              const lastIdx = history.length - 1;
              if (lastIdx > 0) {
                const head = history.slice(0, lastIdx).join(" ") + " ";
                target.appendChild(document.createTextNode(head));
              }
              const tspan = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, "tspan");
              tspan.setAttribute(
                "class",
                fresh ? "epr-history-last epr-history-fresh"
                      : "epr-history-last"
              );
              tspan.textContent = history[lastIdx];
              target.appendChild(tspan);
              if (fresh) {
                const bb = tspan.getBBox();
                bg.setAttribute("x", bb.x - 2);
                bg.setAttribute("y", bb.y - 1);
                bg.setAttribute("width", bb.width + 4);
                bg.setAttribute("height", bb.height + 2);
                bg.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              } else {
                bg.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              }
            }

            function renderHistory() {
              renderHistorySide(aHist, false);
              renderHistorySide(bHist, false);
            }

            function unboldHistory() {
              // Drop the .epr-history-fresh class on whichever
              // tspan still carries it, and clear both side's
              // inversion backdrops. Snap-flip, no CSS transition.
              for (const text of [aHist, bHist]) {
                const tspan = text.querySelector(".epr-history-fresh");
                if (tspan) tspan.classList.remove("epr-history-fresh");
              }
              aHistBg.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              bHistBg.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
            }

            function setPhotonPos(side, x, y) {
              const g = side === "L" ? photonL : photonR;
              g.setAttribute("transform", `translate(${x} ${y})`);
            }

            function showPhoton(side) {
              const g = side === "L" ? photonL : photonR;
              g.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
            }

            function hidePhoton(side) {
              const g = side === "L" ? photonL : photonR;
              g.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
            }

            // Inward leg: photon drawn as a fuzzy cloud (no axis).
            function setGlyphCloud(side) {
              const cloud = side === "L" ? lCloud : rCloud;
              const bar   = side === "L" ? lBar   : rBar;
              cloud.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              bar.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
            }

            // Outward leg: photon drawn as a sharp bar oriented at H
            // (outcome 0) or V (outcome 1).
            function setGlyphBar(side, outcome) {
              const cloud = side === "L" ? lCloud : rCloud;
              const bar   = side === "L" ? lBar   : rBar;
              cloud.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              bar.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              bar.setAttribute("transform", `rotate(${outcome === 0 ? 0 : 90})`);
            }

            function detectorIndeterminate(side) {
              const [zero, one] = side === "A" ? [a0, a1] : [b0, b1];
              zero.setAttribute("opacity", "0.18");
              one.setAttribute("opacity", "0.18");
            }

            function detectorLock(side, outcome) {
              const [zero, one] = side === "A" ? [a0, a1] : [b0, b1];
              if (outcome === 0) {
                zero.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
                one.setAttribute("opacity", "0.08");
              } else {
                zero.setAttribute("opacity", "0.08");
                one.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
              }
            }

            function setKets(outcome /* 0 | 1 | null */) {
              // Active ket: bold + white fill, with its backing rect
              // shown so the digits read as white-on-black. Non-
              // matching ket: dimmed. During flight (outcome null):
              // both kets neutral, both rects hidden.
              const active = (k) => {
                k.classList.add("eps-ket--active");
                k.classList.remove("eps-ket--dim");
              };
              const dim = (k) => {
                k.classList.remove("eps-ket--active");
                k.classList.add("eps-ket--dim");
              };
              const neutral = (k) => {
                k.classList.remove("eps-ket--active");
                k.classList.remove("eps-ket--dim");
              };
              if (outcome === 0) {
                active(k00); dim(k11);
                bg00.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
                bg11.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              } else if (outcome === 1) {
                active(k11); dim(k00);
                bg11.setAttribute("opacity", "1");
                bg00.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              } else {
                neutral(k00); neutral(k11);
                bg00.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
                bg11.setAttribute("opacity", "0");
              }
            }

            // Border-flash state. When a detector fires we set its
            // pulseEnd; the per-frame updateBorders() interpolates
            // its rect stroke-width down to baseline. Keyed by
            // side+outcome so only the detector that clicked flashes.
            const PULSE_DUR = 280;
            const flash = { A0: 0, A1: 0, B0: 0, B1: 0 };
            function pulse(side, outcome, now) {
              flash[`${side}${outcome}`] = now + PULSE_DUR;
            }
            function updateBorders(now) {
              for (const key of ["A0", "A1", "B0", "B1"]) {
                const remaining = flash[key] - now;
                const rect = detRect[key];
                if (remaining > 0) {
                  const t = remaining / PULSE_DUR;
                  rect.setAttribute("stroke-width", String(1.5 + 2.5 * t));
                } else {
                  rect.setAttribute("stroke-width", "1.5");
                }
              }
            }

            const reducedMotion = matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

            if (reducedMotion) {
              hidePhoton("L");
              hidePhoton("R");
              detectorLock("A", 0);
              detectorLock("B", 0);
              setKets(0);
              history.push("0", "1", "1", "0", "1", "0", "0", "1");
              renderHistory();
            } else {
              // Per-side inward (EPS → PBS) travel time. The
              // first-to-measure side travels faster (its photon
              // arrives at its PBS earlier and goes through). The
              // other side arrives at its PBS later. There is no
              // "pause at the PBS" — once the photon arrives, it
              // continues onto the H or V output beam immediately.
              const TRAVEL_IN_FAST  = 1800;
              const TRAVEL_IN_SLOW  = 2400;
              const TRAVEL_OUT      = 550;
              const HOLD            = 700;
              const PAUSE           = 300;
              const FIRST_MEASURE   = TRAVEL_IN_FAST + TRAVEL_OUT;
              const SECOND_MEASURE  = TRAVEL_IN_SLOW + TRAVEL_OUT;
              const TOTAL           = SECOND_MEASURE + HOLD + PAUSE;

              // Pre-generated outcome / firstSide sequences. Pure
              // Math.random() per cycle technically gives uniform
              // independent draws, but humans read long runs of the
              // same value as "not random". We pre-generate length-64
              // sequences capped at 4 consecutive identical values
              // and loop around. The phase offset for the wobble
              // stays continuous-random — no run-perception issue
              // since it's a continuous value, not a coin flip.
              function makeConstrained(length, maxRun) {
                const seq = new Array(length);
                let run = 0;
                let last = -1;
                for (let i = 0; i < length; i++) {
                  let v = Math.random() < 0.5 ? 0 : 1;
                  if (v === last && run >= maxRun) v = 1 - last;
                  seq[i] = v;
                  if (v === last) run++;
                  else { run = 1; last = v; }
                }
                return seq;
              }
              const outcomeSeq   = makeConstrained(64, 4);
              const firstSideSeq = makeConstrained(64, 4);
              let outcomeIdx = 0;
              let firstSideIdx = 0;
              function nextOutcome() {
                const v = outcomeSeq[outcomeIdx];
                outcomeIdx = (outcomeIdx + 1) % outcomeSeq.length;
                return v;
              }
              function nextFirstSide() {
                const v = firstSideSeq[firstSideIdx];
                firstSideIdx = (firstSideIdx + 1) % firstSideSeq.length;
                return v === 0 ? "A" : "B";
              }

              let running = false;
              let cycleStart = 0;
              let outcome = nextOutcome();
              let firstSide = nextFirstSide();
              let firedFirst = false;
              let firedSecond = false;

              const firstLR  = () => firstSide === "A" ? "L" : "R";
              const secondLR = () => firstSide === "A" ? "R" : "L";
              const secondSide = () => firstSide === "A" ? "B" : "A";

              // Per-side trajectory: inward leg as a cloud along the
              // horizontal flight path, then outward leg as an H or V
              // bar along the diagonal output beam.
              function updatePhoton(side, elapsed) {
                const sideAB = side === "L" ? "A" : "B";
                const isFirst = sideAB === firstSide;
                const tIn = isFirst ? TRAVEL_IN_FAST : TRAVEL_IN_SLOW;
                const tDet = tIn + TRAVEL_OUT;
                const srcX = side === "L" ? SRC_L : SRC_R;
                const pbsX = side === "L" ? PBS_L : PBS_R;
                const det = DET_POS[`${sideAB}${outcome}`];

                if (elapsed < tIn) {
                  const p = elapsed / tIn;
                  setPhotonPos(side, srcX + (pbsX - srcX) * p, FLIGHT_Y);
                  setGlyphCloud(side);
                  showPhoton(side);
                } else if (elapsed < tDet) {
                  const p = (elapsed - tIn) / TRAVEL_OUT;
                  setPhotonPos(side,
                               pbsX + (det.x - pbsX) * p,
                               FLIGHT_Y + (det.y - FLIGHT_Y) * p);
                  setGlyphBar(side, outcome);
                  showPhoton(side);
                } else {
                  hidePhoton(side);
                }
              }

              function frame(now) {
                if (!running) return;
                const elapsed = now - cycleStart;

                updatePhoton("L", elapsed);
                updatePhoton("R", elapsed);

                if (elapsed < FIRST_MEASURE) {
                  detectorIndeterminate("A");
                  detectorIndeterminate("B");
                  setKets(null);
                } else if (elapsed < SECOND_MEASURE) {
                  // First side's photon has arrived at its detector.
                  if (!firedFirst) {
                    pulse(firstSide, outcome, now);
                    history.push(String(outcome));
                    if (history.length > HISTORY_LIMIT) history.shift();
                    renderHistorySide(firstSide === "A" ? aHist : bHist, true);
                    firedFirst = true;
                  }
                  detectorLock(firstSide, outcome);
                  detectorIndeterminate(secondSide());
                  setKets(outcome);
                } else if (elapsed < SECOND_MEASURE + HOLD) {
                  // Second side's photon has now arrived.
                  if (!firedSecond) {
                    pulse(secondSide(), outcome, now);
                    renderHistorySide(secondSide() === "A" ? aHist : bHist, true);
                    firedSecond = true;
                  }
                  detectorLock("A", outcome);
                  detectorLock("B", outcome);
                  setKets(outcome);
                } else if (elapsed < TOTAL) {
                  // Brief pause before next cycle.
                } else {
                  // Snap the history back to plain weight + colour
                  // before the next transmission begins; the next
                  // measurement will re-bold whichever side gets the
                  // new digit. No CSS transition — instant flip.
                  unboldHistory();
                  cycleStart = now;
                  outcome = nextOutcome();
                  firstSide = nextFirstSide();
                  firedFirst = false;
                  firedSecond = false;
                }

                updateBorders(now);
                requestAnimationFrame(frame);
              }

              // Continuous animation. We deliberately don't gate on
              // an IntersectionObserver: that approach was resetting
              // cycleStart on re-entry, and the observer can fire on
              // small layout shifts (e.g. hover-triggered repaints),
              // perceived as a "restart". requestAnimationFrame is
              // already throttled when the browser tab is hidden, so
              // running unconditionally costs essentially nothing
              // when the figure is off-screen.
              running = true;
              cycleStart = performance.now();
              requestAnimationFrame(frame);
            }
          }
        </script>
      </section>

      <section id="bell-pairs" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The four Bell pairs</h2>
        <p>
          There are exactly four <strong>maximally entangled</strong> two-qubit states — the
          Bell states. They form an orthonormal basis for the two-qubit Hilbert space and
          are the resource on which every quantum-network protocol is built.
        </p>

        <div class="bell-grid">
          <article class="bell-card">
            <h3 class="bell-card__name">|Φ⁺⟩</h3>
            <Math display tex="\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\bigl(|00\\rangle + |11\\rangle\\bigr)" />
            <p>Even parity, symmetric phase. The reference Bell state in most protocols.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="bell-card">
            <h3 class="bell-card__name">|Φ⁻⟩</h3>
            <Math display tex="\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\bigl(|00\\rangle - |11\\rangle\\bigr)" />
            <p>Even parity, opposite phase. Reached from |Φ⁺⟩ by applying <Math tex="Z" /> to
              either qubit.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="bell-card">
            <h3 class="bell-card__name">|Ψ⁺⟩</h3>
            <Math display tex="\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\bigl(|01\\rangle + |10\\rangle\\bigr)" />
            <p>Odd parity, symmetric phase. From |Φ⁺⟩ by applying <Math tex="X" /> to either
              qubit.</p>
          </article>

          <article class="bell-card">
            <h3 class="bell-card__name">|Ψ⁻⟩</h3>
            <Math display tex="\\tfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\bigl(|01\\rangle - |10\\rangle\\bigr)" />
            <p>The <strong>singlet</strong> — antisymmetric, the unique rotationally invariant
              Bell state. From |Φ⁺⟩ by applying <Math tex="XZ" /> to either qubit.</p>
          </article>
        </div>

        <Callout label="Why exactly four">
          <p>
            Two qubits live in a 4-dimensional Hilbert space, and a maximally entangled state
            is one whose reduced density matrix on either side is the maximally mixed state
            <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{2}\\mathbb{I}" />. The set of such states forms a basis of
            the joint Hilbert space — there are exactly four orthogonal such states up to a
            global phase, the Bell states. Local single-qubit Pauli operations
            (<Math tex="X" />, <Math tex="Z" />, <Math tex="XZ" />) on one side convert any
            Bell state into any other, so a network only needs to deliver one canonical pair
            (typically <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle" />); the receiver reaches the others by
            local action.
          </p>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="why-deliver" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Why deliver Bell pairs</h2>
        <p>
          A network could in principle ferry an arbitrary unknown qubit
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> from sender to receiver — the quantum analogue of
          a classical packet. The universally adopted approach is the other one: deliver
          a fixed, known state — a Bell pair — and let the application extract whatever
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> it wants at the endpoints. Two properties make
          Bell pairs the right resource <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Maximally entangled.</strong> No two-qubit state has stronger
            entanglement than a Bell pair. An application running an entanglement-based
            protocol cannot do better than the resource it consumes, and Bell pairs are
            the strongest resource available.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Convertible to any state by local operations.</strong> Once Alice and
            Bob share a Bell pair, any desired two-qubit state can be produced from it by
            single-qubit gates applied locally at each end, plus two classical bits
            exchanged between them. Distributing Bell pairs is therefore enough to
            support every entanglement-based application at the endpoints.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The alternative — encoding an unknown qubit into a quantum-error-correcting
          code and sending the encoded block directly through the lossy channel — is the
          <strong>third-generation quantum repeater</strong> approach. It eliminates the
          round-trip latency that gen 1 and 2 repeaters incur, but at QEC overheads well
          above what current hardware delivers. Until that matures, Bell-pair distribution
          plus teleportation is what works in practice, and what every fielded
          entanglement-distribution experiment to date uses. The
          <strong>repeaters</strong> subject later in the series goes into the gen 1 / 2 / 3
          trade-offs in
          detail <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" /><SourceNote id="muralidharan-scirep-2016" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="uses" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What a Bell pair lets you do</h2>
        <p>
          A single qubit's state cannot be copied. The <strong>no-cloning theorem</strong>
          says there is no unitary <Math tex="U" /> for which
          <Math tex="U(|\\psi\\rangle|0\\rangle) = |\\psi\\rangle|\\psi\\rangle" /> for an
          arbitrary unknown <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />; copying would violate the
          linearity of quantum mechanics <SourceNote id="wootters-nature-1982" />. A signal
          photon cannot be passed through an amplifier and faithfully reproduced either —
          any phase-insensitive amplifier must add at least one quantum of noise per mode,
          which destroys the qubit's state. The consequence is that quantum networks cannot
          reuse the engineering that makes long-distance classical optical fibre work; the
          three primitives below replace it.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each consumes the shared Bell pair (one-shot resource) and uses a classical
          side-channel for the corrections that complete the protocol.
        </p>

        <Grid min="18rem" gap="var(--space-3)">
          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Teleportation</h3>
            <p>
              Alice has an unknown qubit <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> she wants to transmit
              to Bob. She performs a Bell-state measurement on
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> together with her half of the shared Bell pair,
              then sends the 2-bit outcome to Bob over a classical channel. Bob applies the
              corresponding Pauli correction to his half — which is now in state
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. The original at Alice is destroyed in the
              measurement, consistent with no-cloning <SourceNote id="bennett-prl-1993" />.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Entanglement swapping</h3>
            <p>
              Alice and a relay station share a Bell pair; the relay and Bob share another.
              The relay performs a Bell-state measurement on its two qubits and sends the
              2-bit result to one of the endpoints, who applies a Pauli correction. Alice
              and Bob now share a Bell pair, even though their qubits never interacted. The
              primitive every memory-based quantum repeater is built
              on <SourceNote id="zukowski-prl-1993" />.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="use-card">
            <h3>Distillation</h3>
            <p>
              Bell pairs delivered through a noisy channel are mixed states with reduced
              fidelity. Distillation protocols consume two (or more) low-fidelity pairs and
              produce one higher-fidelity pair, trading throughput for quality. Together
              with swapping, distillation makes long-distance entanglement distribution
              feasible without per-photon error correction
              <SourceNote id="bennett-pra-1996" />.
            </p>
          </article>
        </Grid>
      </section>

      <section id="generation" data-nav-section>
        <h2>How Bell pairs are made</h2>
        <p>
          The three primitives above all <em>consume</em> Bell pairs. This section covers
          how a pair is <em>generated</em> — what physical device produces the entangled
          state in the first place. How a generated pair is then <em>distributed</em>
          (one half placed at each of two distant nodes) is a separate engineering
          subject covered later in the series <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>

        <Callout label="Postselection vs heralding">
          <p>
            Photonic measurement is destructive — a detection consumes the photon — which
            forces a choice for any scheme that <em>generates</em> entanglement using
            measurement.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Postselected</strong>: every photon is measured, and successful events
            are filtered out of the data afterwards. No entangled state survives the
            procedure — only measurement records that match what an entangled state would
            have produced.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Heralded</strong>: some of the photons in the apparatus are dedicated
            to signalling success rather than carrying the state. These auxiliary photons
            — <strong>ancilla</strong> photons, the standard quantum-information term for
            auxiliary particles introduced to serve a protocol rather than carry its
            output — are routed to dedicated detectors and consumed there. A specific
            click pattern at those detectors confirms that the <em>other</em> photons in
            the apparatus, which are not measured, form the desired entangled state and
            are available for downstream use. Each attempt is therefore known in real
            time to have succeeded or failed <SourceNote id="forbes-rpp-2025" />.
          </p>

