              photon at measurement; the click pattern is the only output.
              <strong>Heralding</strong> (right) routes a subset (orange) to ancilla
              detectors whose click pattern certifies the un-measured target modes
              (purple) — those photons survive in the entangled state
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />, ready for the next protocol step.
            </figcaption>
          </figure>

          <p>
            For a network that must <em>deliver</em> entanglement so downstream protocols
            can teleport, swap, or distil, heralding is the only viable choice — every
            architecture below relies on it. Postselection remains useful when the
            protocol only needs the classical measurement record at the end. <strong>QKD</strong>
            is the canonical example: BBM92 and Ekert91 entanglement-based QKD use
            coincidence-window postselection plus basis-sifting; MDI-QKD postselects on
            the central node's Bell-state-measurement announcement; even prepare-and-measure
            BB84 sifts (postselects) basis-matched events to build the raw key. None of
            these need a quantum state to survive after measurement, which is why
            postselection works for them.
          </p>
        </Callout>

        <p>
          Different platforms produce entangled pairs in different ways, all of them
          probabilistic and heralded:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Spontaneous parametric down-conversion (SPDC)</strong> in a non-linear
            crystal (PPKTP, BBO, PPLN). A pump photon spontaneously splits into two
            lower-energy photons whose polarisation, time-energy, and momentum are
            correlated by the conservation laws of the conversion. Megahertz pair rates,
            broad bandwidth, room temperature; the workhorse for QKD field deployments and
            Micius-style satellite experiments
            <SourceNote id="kwiat-prl-1995" /><SourceNote id="yin-science-2017" />. The
            chip-integrated variant, <strong>spontaneous four-wave mixing (SFWM)</strong>
            in silicon-photonic waveguides, puts the same physics on a chip.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Atomic-ensemble emission (DLCZ-style)</strong>. A cloud of cold atoms
            emits a Stokes photon entangled with a delocalised collective spin-wave
            excitation in the ensemble. The ensemble doubles as a memory; reading it out
            later releases an idler photon entangled with whatever Bell pair was generated
            <SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" /><SourceNote id="duan-nature-414" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Single-emitter matter-photon entanglement</strong>. A trapped ion,
            neutral atom, NV or SiV centre in diamond, or semiconductor quantum dot emits
            a photon entangled with its own internal spin or hyperfine level. The matter
            qubit then holds the entanglement while the photon travels
            <SourceNote id="knaut-nature-2024" />.
          </li>
        </ul>

      </section>

      <section id="requirements" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What it takes to deliver Bell pairs</h2>
        <p>
          The link-layer service of a quantum network is <q>deliver Bell pair (A, B)</q>
          on demand <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />. Once delivered, the application
          layer can teleport, distil, swap, or measure as it likes. The network does not
          transport classical messages or copy arbitrary qubits — it distributes
          entanglement between named endpoints, and everything else is built on top.
        </p>
        <p>
          Providing that service end-to-end requires every piece below working at adequate
          rate, fidelity, and reach. Each is a separate engineering challenge, covered in
          a dedicated subject later in the series.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Sources</strong> — generate the entangled pairs in the first place
            (SPDC, atomic-ensemble, single-emitter). <em>Covered above.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Distribution</strong> — place one half of a generated pair at each of
            two distant nodes across a single link, via one of the MM / SR / MS
            architectures. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distribution</strong>
            <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Memory</strong> — hold a qubit while its partner photon is in flight,
            with coherence longer than the link's classical round-trip.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>memories</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Reach extension</strong> — chain Bell-state measurements across
            multiple hops so entanglement spans further than a single link can reach.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>swapping</strong> <em>and</em>
            <strong>repeaters</strong> <em>subjects.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Fidelity extension</strong> — distillation trades two noisy pairs for
            one cleaner pair, so the delivered fidelity is high enough for downstream use.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>distillation</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Physical channel</strong> — fibre, hollow-core fibre, free-space, or
            satellite. Loss bounds reach; the channel choice sets the loss budget.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>links</strong> <em>and</em>
            <strong>metrics</strong> <em>subjects.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Protocol stack</strong> — link-layer scheduling, routing, addressing,
            and the classical side-channel needed by every protocol on this page.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>protocols</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
